Eric retreated and Diandre pulled out a gun and shot him in the abdomen, piercing his stomach and several other organs. Clutching the wound, Eric walked back to his family while Diandre fled the area.

Diandre claims that Eric was making "threatening gestures" which forced him to defend himself. In a motion he put forth during his trial, Diandre wrote, "I protected mine and my family‚Äôs life‚Äôs, nuthing more nuthing less." According to the prosecutor, a video of the confrontation contradicts this account. Diandre's first murder trial ended with a hung jury.

According to WSJ, at a certain point after the start of the Special Operation, Kazakhstan decided to reconsider its relations with Russia and began to look for allies in the United States, Turkey and China.   
  
Beginning in April, several officials from the United States visited Kazakhstan. For example, the new head of U.S. Central Command, Army General Michael Eric Kurilla, visited the country in June. At the same time, Kazakhstan increased its defense budget by 441 billion tenge (about $915 million).   
  
And in early May, Tokayev flew to Ankara, where representatives of the two countries signed an agreement on joint production of Bayraktar drones in Kazakhstan.    
  
There's more.  Kazakhstan decided to ban the public display of the Z symbol.   
  
And after Tony Blair made a secret visit to Kazakhstan in late May, Kazakh President Kassym-Jomart Tokayev, speaking at the St. Petersburg Economic Forum, in the presence of Russian President Vladimir Putin, called the DNR and LNR quasi-state territories and said that Kazakhstan would not recognize them.  
  
In fact, now, on the basis of Kazakhstan, they are building a bastion of the future Turan. It can no longer be called even a creeping occupation. The situation is more than alarming. And it is not considering the fact that Kazakhstan, being the member of Eurasian Union, is trying to pull over the economic levers and to shelter business which left Russia, becoming a kind of alternative financial center of EEC.  
  
According to our information Kazakhstan was recently visited by former British Prime Minister Tony Blair who met with the leadership of the republic.
 
They discussed steps to sabotage Kazakhstan's participation and work in the CSTO.
